CORD-19 TF-IDF Complete Notebook¶

This notebook is my contribution to the Kaggle competition : COVID-19 Open Research Dataset Challenge (CORD-19)

The dataset is composed of 29 327 scientific articles which are to be processed in order to find information about some 'tasks' (like : - 'Range of incubation periods for the disease in humans (and how this varies across age and health status) and how long individuals are contagious, even after recovery.'), without, obviously, having to read all the documents.

Features

  • Plots in 2-Dimensions of the text dataset with clustering
  • Search of the most approriate sentences / documents for every tasks
  • Free text search

Implementation

The ultimate goal of this notebook is to create a Bokeh Dashboard with every of those features.

Text Representation

In this notebook, the modelisation of the text is based on TF-IDF.

For Word-Embeddings based techniques, please see my other notebook in this repo and don't hesitate to compare the results.

Main ideas and steps

  • Firstly:
    • TFIDF cosine similarity to find the most accurate sentences
    • Retrieving of the original document (to not have the sentences in an unreadable way)

  • Then :

    • Indexing the sentences

    • Preprocessing/tfidf to find the indexes of the sentences which are relevant.

    • Picking a few from their scores (the 3/5 best ones, or the ones above a similarity score given a threshold, or both options combined together)

To perform a better visualization of the documents :

  • PCA / LDA or t-SNE
  • K-means to make clusters
  • Chi-2 scores to see the most relevant words for each cluster

We could even make a button next to an article to see its position compared to others

Preprocessing data :¶

In order to clean our dataset, we are going to :

  • lemmatize the text
  • remove stop words

I could have used already implemented functions, but to have complete control over the procedures implemented to format the text, I have written a custom function, with the help of this and this.

There are several steps, including:

  • Normalization
  • removing the punctuation
  • removing stop words
  • lemmatize the text
In [18]:
#Defining the global variable
global spacy_nlp
#Loading the english model of Spacy
spacy_nlp = spacy.load('en_core_web_sm')

def normalize(text):
    #function to normalize the text using the normalise package
    # some issues in normalise package
    try:
        return ' '.join(normalise(text,tokenizer=word_tokenize,verbose=False))
    except:
        return text
    
def remove_punct(doc):
    #Function to remove punctation
    return [t for t in doc if t.text not in string.punctuation]

def remove_stop_words(doc):
    #Function to remove stopwords
    return [t for t in doc if not t.is_stop]

def lemmatize(doc):
    #Function to lemmatize the articles
    return ' '.join([t.lemma_ for t in doc])
    
def preprocessing_part(text):
    #Function applying every other functions written above
    normalized_text=normalize(text).lower()
    doc=spacy_nlp(normalized_text)
    removed_punct=remove_punct(doc)
    removed_stop_words=remove_stop_words(removed_punct)
    return lemmatize(removed_stop_words)

Functions to retrieve information:¶

In this part of the notebook, I have written several functions, all based on a TF-IDF representation of the text, to retrieve information about the articles.

Some functions permits to find similar articles from another, given its index, and to export results in html, to be used in the Bokeh Dashboard described at the end of the notebook.

Some other functions do quite the same things, but with either a free text entry or a query as defined in the kaggle tasks.

At the end, a final function is implemented to do everything from one function.

Function to find similar documents from its index:¶

In [19]:
def find_similar_from_index(tfidf_matrix, index, top_n = 5):
    """
    Function find_similar to find the similar documents of one given document, given its index in the corpus. 
    
    @Inputs : 
        - tfidf_matrix : matrix returned by the tfidf transformation of the entire corpus
        - index : the index of the document
        - top_n : the number of articles similar to be shown
    
    @Outputs :
        - indexes_scores_docs, a list with the indexes and the cosine similarity scores of the top n (top_n) 
        most similar articles. 
    """
    cosine_similarities = linear_kernel(tfidf_matrix[index:index+1], tfidf_matrix).flatten()
    related_docs_indices = [i for i in cosine_similarities.argsort()[::-1] if i != index]
    indexes_scores_docs = [(index, cosine_similarities[index]) for index in related_docs_indices][0:top_n]
    return indexes_scores_docs

Function to export the similar documents:¶

This function is used to export the results of the find_similar_from_index function in an html way, to be used in the Bokeh Dashboard.

def print_similar_documents(df_covid, tfidf_matrix, index, top_n =5):   
    #We firstly compute the indices and scores of the similar documents:
    indexes_scores_docs=find_similar_from_index(tfidf_matrix, index, top_n)
    #The we compute the html code to print results:
    h='<h3>Similar articles to : "<i>'+df_covid.iloc[index]['title']+'</i>"</h3>'
    for index_article, score_article in indexes_scores_articles:
        article=df_covid.iloc[index_article]
        title=str(article.title)
        #Link of the article:
        link=str(article.link)
        authors=str(article.authors)
        #We plot the general information about the article : 
        h+='<ul> <li><a href="'+link+'" target="_blank">'+title+'</a>, by '+ authors +',  (Similarity Score: ' + "{:.2f}".format(score_article) + ')</li></ul>' 
    return h

Function to find documents similar to a given query, and making the transformation :¶

In [21]:
def find_documents_from_query(tfidf_matrix, tfidf_query, top_n=5):
    """
    Function find_documents_from_query, which computes the top_n most relevent articles given the tfidf representation
    of the query
    
    @Inputs:
    - tfidf_matrix, the tfidf matrix representation of the entire set of articles
    - tfidf_query, the tfidf vector representation of the query
    - top_n = 5, the number of documents to find
    @Outputs: 
    indexes_scores, the index of each top_n article in the DataFrame, and the associated cosine_similarity score
    """
    #We calculate the cosine similarity between the query and each document:
    cosine_similarities = linear_kernel(tfidf_query, tfidf_matrix).flatten()
    #We sort the documents from the similarit to the query :
    related_docs_indices = [i for i in cosine_similarities.argsort()[::-1]]
    #We retrieve the top n documents most similar to the given query :
    indexes_scores = [(index, cosine_similarities[index]) for index in related_docs_indices][0:top_n]
    return indexes_scores

Function to export the sentences most relevent from each article :¶

For this purpose, we need to :

  • index each sentences of the given articles
  • perform TF-IDF on the set of sentences
  • Compare the query with each sentence using cosine similarity

For the last task, we can easily use the function find_similar, just like before.

If we perform reduction on the documents to plot each documents with the distance to the other, we could also do the same with the sentences.

  • Then, we show the relevent sentences, given a criteria :
    • We can use a threshold on the similarity score
    • We can also use a number of sentences to show, but this could end up showing sentences completely out of context

Therefore, I think we can use both.

Warning :

We must index the sentences before making any transformation to the text !!!

To avoid empty sentences (with the lemmatisation), we can show either a number of characters or sentences before and after the one chosen.

We can also verify that two sentences are not one after the other.

Function to index the sentences of an article:¶

I use the method descibed here to index the sentences of the articles:

In [22]:
def sentence_indexing(article):
    """
    Function sentence_indexing made to index the sentences of an article
    
    @Inputs: 
    article, the text of the article
    
    @Outputs:
    df_sentences, a pandas DataFrame, with a single column 'sentences', corresponding to each sentences of the article
                    Obviously, the indexing is then performed directly in the pandas DataFrame.
    """
    #We split the article for each '.' encountered, this gives every sentences of the text, which we then store in the
    #Pandas DataFrame 'df_sentences'.
    #We also verify that the sentences are not empty (because of a typo or because of the lemmatization)
    #df_sentences=pd.DataFrame({'sentences': [sentence for sentence in article.split('.') if sentence !='']})
    
    
    doc=spacy_nlp(article)
    df_sentences=pd.DataFrame({'sentences':[sentence.text for sentence in doc.sents]})
    
    return df_sentences

As explained before, since this kind of task can be very long, I performed this preprocessing before and stored it in df_preprocessed_covid. This aims at reducing the computational time.

Function to find the sentences most relevant for each article found :¶
In [23]:
def index_relevant_sentences(df_preprocessed_covid, tfidf, index_article, tfidf_query, top_n_sentences=5):
    """
    Function relevant_sentences, which computes for a given query the most relevant sentences inside an article.
    
    @Inputs: 
    df_preprocessed_covid
    tfidf, the tfidf model
    index_article, the index of the article
    tfidf_query, the given query, transformed after tfidf
    top_n_sentences
    
    @Outputs : 
    index_score, the index and the score of the most relevant sentences (sorted)
    """
    d={'sentences':df_preprocessed_covid.iloc[index_article]['list_preprocessed_sentences']}
    df_preprocessed_sentences=pd.DataFrame(data=d)
    #We transform the sentences with tfidf:
    article_sentences_tfidf = tfidf.transform(df_preprocessed_sentences['sentences'])
    #We find the most relevant articles given the query, using find_document:
    index_scores = find_documents_from_query(article_sentences_tfidf, tfidf_query, top_n_sentences)
    return index_scores

Function to transform the query with the tf-idf model :¶
In [25]:
def transform_query(tfidf, query):
    """
    Function transform_query, which takes the tfidf model and a query, to preprocess it and transform it in a usable form
    @Inputs: 
    tfidf, the tfidf model, fit on the entire corpus
    query, the given str query 
    
    @Outputs: 
    tfidf_query, the transformed query, after cleaning, preprocessing, lemmatization and tfidf transformation    
    """
    preprocessed_query = preprocessing_part(query)
    tfidf_query = tfidf.transform([preprocessed_query]).toarray()
    return tfidf_query
Function to transform the entire text:¶
In [26]:
def transform_text(df_preprocessed_covid, column='body_text'):
    """
    Function transform_text fitting the tfidf transformation and applying it to transform the articles
    @Inputs: 
        - df_preprocessed_covid, the dataframe with the articles
        - column, the column in the dataframe concerned with this modification
    @Outputs: 
        - tfidf, the tfidf model
        - tfidf_matrix, the tfidf matrix of the set of articles
    """
    df_preprocessed_covid[column] = df_preprocessed_covid[column].fillna(' ')
    # Initializing TFIDF :
    tfidf = TfidfVectorizer(sublinear_tf=True, min_df=5, norm='l2', encoding='latin-1', ngram_range=(1,1), max_features=10000)
    
    #Defining the features needed :
    tfidf_matrix = tfidf.fit_transform(df_preprocessed_covid[column]).toarray()
    return tfidf, tfidf_matrix

Final function, taking a query, transforming it, returning the most relevant articles and the most relevent sentences inside those articles¶
In [28]:
def find_answers(df_covid, df_preprocessed_covid, query,tfidf=tfidf,tfidf_matrix=tfidf_matrix, column='body_text',top_n_sentences=5, top_n_articles=5):
    """
    Function find_answers to find the most relevent sentences inside the most relevant articles 
    @Inputs:
        - df_covid, the DataFrame associated with the plain untransformed articles
        - df_preprocessed_covid, the DataFrame with the articles preprocessed (would be very long to perform this on each
            call of this function)
        - query, str, the plain query, to be transformed
        - tfidf, the tfidf model
        - tfidf_matrix, the tfidf matrix already computed
        - column, str, the text column to be processed
        - top_n_sentences : the number of sentences to select
        - top_n_articles : the number of articles to select
    
    @Outputs:
        - index_score_articles_sentences, a DataFrame, containing the indexes of the articles and the sentences of the
        articles, and the associated scores by cosine similarity
    """
    #Firstly, we compute empty lists to store indexes and scores:
    L_index_articles, L_index_sentences, L_scores_articles, L_scores_sentences= [],[],[],[]
    #We transform by tfidf the preprocessed dataset, selecting the needed column
    #tfidf, tfidf_matrix = transform_text(df_preprocessed_covid, column)
    #We transform the query : 
    tfidf_query=transform_query(tfidf, query)
    #We want to find the most relevant articles for this query : 
    #We compute the indexes of the relevant articles and their associated cosine similarity score
    indexes_scores_articles = find_documents_from_query(tfidf_matrix, tfidf_query, top_n=top_n_articles)
    #Since we have the indexes, we can have the articles, and find the sentences most relevent inside each article: 
    for index_article, score_article in indexes_scores_articles:
        #Here, since we need to index the sentences of the articles, we take the df_covid, not preprocessed, DataFrame
        
        index_score_sentences=index_relevant_sentences(df_preprocessed_covid,tfidf,
                                                       index_article, tfidf_query, top_n_sentences)       
        
        for index_sentence, score_sentence in index_score_sentences:
            #We store the wanted data in the associated lists:
            L_index_articles.append(index_article)
            L_index_sentences.append(index_sentence)
            L_scores_articles.append(score_article)
            L_scores_sentences.append(score_sentence)
    #Finally, we compute the DataFrame we want to return 
    d={'index_article' : L_index_articles , 'score_article': L_scores_articles, 'index_sentence':  L_index_sentences,
       'score_sentence':L_scores_sentences } 
    index_score_articles_sentences=pd.DataFrame(data=d)
    return index_score_articles_sentences

def compute_articles_sentences(index_score_articles_sentences, df_covid, h):
    """
    Function compute_articles_sentences which permits to store information about the most relevent articles 
    and their associated relevent sentences """
    
    
    for index_article in index_score_articles_sentences['index_article'].unique(): 
        #We compute the score of the article: 
        score_article=index_score_articles_sentences[index_score_articles_sentences['index_article']==index_article].score_article.iloc[0]
        #We compte the information about the article from the df_covid DataFrame with its associated index:
        article=df_covid.iloc[index_article]
        #Title of the article:
        title=str(article.title)
        #Link of the article:
        link=str(article.link)
        authors=str(article.authors)
        #We plot the general information about the article : 
        h+='<br/><a href="'+link+'" target="_blank">'+title+'</a>, by '+ authors +',  (Similarity Score: ' + "{:.2f}".format(score_article) + ')' 
        
        #We need to index the sentences of the article:         
        d={'sentences':df_preprocessed_covid.iloc[index_article]['list_sentences']}
        df_sentences=pd.DataFrame(data=d)
        s=index_score_articles_sentences[index_score_articles_sentences['index_article']==index_article]
        index_sentences=s['index_sentence']
        for index_sentence in index_sentences:
            sentence=df_sentences.iloc[index_sentence]['sentences']
            score_sentence=s[s['index_sentence']==index_sentence]['score_sentence'].iloc[0]
            if score_sentence>0.01:
                h+='<ul> <li>' + sentence+ '. (Similarity score: '+ '{:.2f}'.format(score_sentence) +')</li></ul>'
    return h

def compute_whole_answer(index_score_articles_sentences, df_covid, query, n_sentences=2):
    """

    @Inputs:
    -index_score_articles_sentences
    -df_covid
    -query
    -n_sentences=2
    @Output:
    -h
    """

    #Fisrtly, we compute the two most relevent sentences:
    h+='<h4> Most relevent sentences found : </h4>'
    #Computing them by sorting on the sentences scores:
    best_sentences=index_score_articles_sentences.sort_values(by=['score_sentence'], ascending=False)[:n_sentences]
    for index, b_sent in best_sentences.iterrows():   
        index_article=b_sent['index_article'].astype(int)
        article=df_covid.iloc[index_article]
        
        
        
        
        d={'sentences':df_preprocessed_covid.iloc[index_article]['list_sentences']}
        df_sentences=pd.DataFrame(data=d)   
        
        
        
        
        index_sentence=b_sent['index_sentence'].astype(int)
        score_sentence=b_sent['score_sentence']
        sentence=df_sentences.iloc[index_sentence]['sentences']
        h+='<ul><li>'+sentence+ '(Similarity score: '+ '{:.2f}'.format(score_sentence) +')</li></ul>'

Taking the most correlated unigrams to get information about each cluster:¶

We can help ourselves with that article and this scikit-learn documentation.

We define the function correlations_grams below to obtain the result.

In [38]:
def correlations_grams(tfidf_matrix, df, tfidf,column_label_name='cluster', N=2):
    """
    function to get the most correlated n-grams associated with each cluster
    @Inputs:
        - tfidf_matrix, the tf_idf matrix
        - df, Pandas DataFrame, the DataFrame with both principal component and one column with the indication on the cluster
        - tfidf, the tfidf model
        - n, int, the number unigrams to obtain
    @Output:
        Corresponding_Grams, the list of the wanted corresponding unigrams
    """
    labels=df[column_label_name]
    unique_labels=labels.unique()
    #We set up the list Corresponding_Grams that we want to return:
    Corresponding_Grams=[]
    for label in unique_labels:
        features_chi2 = chi2(tfidf_matrix, labels == label)
        indices = np.argsort(features_chi2[0])
        feature_names = np.array(tfidf.get_feature_names())[indices]
        unigrams = [v for v in feature_names if len(v.split(' ')) == 1]        
        #We store the results:
        Corresponding_Grams.append(unigrams[-N:])
    return Corresponding_Grams

We can also define two other functions to be used in the definition of the Dashboard.

In [39]:
def print_corresponding_grams(Corresponding_Grams):
    """
    function print_corresponding_grams to plot the corresponding grams to a label
    @Inputs:
    -Corresponding_Grams
    @Output:
    -h
    """
    h=''
    i=0
    for unigrams in Corresponding_Grams:
        h+="<h3>For the label : '{}':</h3>".format(i)
        h+="<h4>. Most correlated unigrams:</h4>{}".format('-'.join(unigrams))
        i+=1
    return h

def associate_corresponding_grams(Corresponding_Grams, df, column_label_name='cluster'):
    """
    Function associate_corresponding_grams which associates the grams most correlated with each cluster
    Please be careful, this function applies the transformation to the DataFrame in input.
    
    @Inputs:
    - Corresponding_Grams
    - df
    - column_label_name
    @Output:
    - df, the DataFrame
    """
    df['label_corresponding_name']=df[column_label_name]
    dictionnary={int(i) : str(Corresponding_Grams[i]) for i in range(len(Corresponding_Grams))}
    df['label_corresponding_name'].replace(dictionnary, inplace=True)
    return df

Defining a function for dimensionnality reduction and clustering¶

In [40]:
def reduction_clustering(tfidf_matrix, tfidf, number_clusters=10):
    """
    Function reduction_clustering to make both the reduction on a DataFrame and to cluster the data
    We use PCA for the reduction and Kmeans for the clustering part
    
    @Inputs:
    - tfidf_matrix
    - tfidf
    - number_clusters
    @Outputs:
    - finalDf, the DataFrame containg the wanted information.
        Column: 'principal component 1', the first coordinate by PCA
                'principal component 2', the second coordinate by PCA
                'cluster', the cluster of the row returned by KMeans
    - PCA, the trained PCA model
    - kmeans, the trained KMeans model
    - Corresponding_Grams
    """
    reduction_model = PCA(n_components=2)
    principalComponents=reduction_model.fit_transform(tfidf_matrix)
    df_reduction = pd.DataFrame(data = principalComponents, columns = ['principal component 1', 'principal component 2'])
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=number_clusters)
    labels = kmeans.fit_predict(tfidf_matrix)
    data_labels={'cluster': labels}
    df_labels=pd.DataFrame(data=data_labels)
    finalDf = pd.concat([df_reduction, df_labels], axis = 1)    
    Corresponding_Grams=correlations_grams(tfidf_matrix,finalDf,tfidf)
    finalDf=associate_corresponding_grams(Corresponding_Grams, finalDf)
    return finalDf, reduction_model, kmeans, Corresponding_Grams

Then, we can compute directly the dimensionnality reduction, the clustering algorithm, and the DataFrame associated with the data we want to obtain.

The lines after the computation of the function above permits to save the results and avoid executing it every time.

def my_covid_app(doc):
    #We can make a function to indicate that a time consuming function is executing, via a gif in a div for exemple.
    def loading(name_div):
        #Insted of a gif image, we could use:
        #https://creativecommons.org/2017/12/07/one-week-left-save-internet/
        name_div.text="""<img src="Dashboard/images/loading_gif_white.gif" height="250" width="400"> </img>"""
    #---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------#
    #---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------#
    #---------------------------First TAB--------------------------------------------------------------------#
    #---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------#
    #---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------#
    
    #We define properly the source of data:
    source = ColumnDataSource(data=finalDf)
    
    #We define the entire plot for the first tab: 
    p = figure(plot_width=600, plot_height=500, 
               tools=["tap", "pan","wheel_zoom","box_zoom","reset"],  
               title='PCA of the articles, clustering by k-means')

    
    #We need to map the colors :
    # map colors
    lower_cluster=min(finalDf['cluster'])
    higher_cluster=max(finalDf['cluster'])
    map_color = linear_cmap(field_name='cluster', palette=Category10[10], low=lower_cluster, high=higher_cluster)
    
    
    #We define the scatterplot with circle:
    p.circle('principal component 1', 'principal component 2', source=source,alpha=0.8,
                 muted_color=map_color, muted_alpha=0.2, 
                 legend='cluster', fill_color=map_color, name='articles_rep')
                
    
    
    
    
    task_selection = Select(title="Task",options=task_name, value='What is known about transmission, incubation, and environmental stability?')
    query_selection= Select(title="Query of the selected task:", 
                            options = list(tasks['What is known about transmission, incubation, and environmental stability?']), 
                            value='Range of incubation periods for the disease in humans (and how this varies across age and health status) and how long individuals are contagious, even after recovery.') 
    number_articles= Slider(title="Number of articles to show", start=0, end=10, step=1, value=5)
    number_sentences= Slider(title="Number of sentences per article to show", start=0, end=10, step=1, value=5)
    
    
    
    
        
    #RangeSlider to select years:
    min_year=1970
    max_year=max(finalDf['year'])
    slider_year=RangeSlider(start=min_year, end=max_year, value=(min_year, max_year), 
                            step=1, title = 'Publish year range', width=200)
    
    
    
    #Checkbox to select (or not) even the unknown years:
    checkbox_year=CheckboxGroup(labels=["All years"], active=[0], width=150)
 

    
    def update_button_year():
        if "All years" in [checkbox_year.labels[i] for i in checkbox_year.active]:
            slider_year.value=(min_year,max_year)
            data=finalDf
            source.data=ColumnDataSource.from_df(data)
        else:
            scale = slider_year.value        
            data=finalDf[finalDf['year'].between(scale[0],scale[1])]
            source.data=ColumnDataSource.from_df(data)
    
    def all_year_selection_checkbox(attr,old,new):
        if "All years" in [checkbox_year.labels[i] for i in checkbox_year.active]:
            slider_year.value=(min_year,max_year)
    
    def all_year_selection_slider(attr,old,new):
        if slider_year.value != (min_year, max_year):
            checkbox_year.active=[]
        else:
            checkbox_year.active=[0]
        
    
    validate_button_year=Button(label='Check visualization for the selected years', height=80)
    validate_button_year.on_click(update_button_year)   
    
    # Attach the all_year_selection_slider callback to the 'value' property of slider_year
    slider_year.on_change('value', all_year_selection_slider)
    #We do the same and attach the all_year_selection_checkbox callback to the 'active' property of the checkbox_year
    checkbox_year.on_change('active',all_year_selection_checkbox)
    
    
    
    
    #We define the callback to update the query to the selected task:
    #https://stackoverflow.com/questions/56278118/python-how-to-dynamically-change-options-in-bokeh-select-widget
    def update_query(attr, old, new):
        task_selected = task_selection.value
        query_selection.options = list(tasks[task_selected])
        query_selection.value = list(tasks[task_selected])[0]

        
        

    #We plot the answers to the query:
    #the part "style={'overflow-y':'scroll', 'height':'350px'}" permits to not overflow the figure and the app
    query_selected=query_selection.value
    index_score_articles_sentences=find_answers(df_covid, df_preprocessed_covid, query_selected, 
                                                    top_n_articles=number_articles.value, 
                                                    top_n_sentences=number_sentences.value)
    h=compute_whole_answer(index_score_articles_sentences, df_covid, query_selected)
    div_html_response = Div(text=h, style={'overflow-y':'scroll', 'height':'350px', 'width':'350px'})   
    
    
    #We define the callback function to update the answer to the selected query:
    def update_answer():
        #We take the value of the query:
        query_selected=query_selection.value
        
            
            
        index_score_articles_sentences=find_answers(df_covid, df_preprocessed_covid, query_selected, 
                                                    top_n_articles=number_articles.value, 
                                                    top_n_sentences=number_sentences.value)
        h=compute_whole_answer(index_score_articles_sentences, df_covid, query_selected)
        div_html_response.text=h
        #We update the representation of the query in the plot:
        update_representation_query()
        
        
    def loading_updating_answer(attr, old, new):
        #To be able to show that the work is in progress, 
        #We use that : https://discourse.bokeh.org/t/show-loading-sign-during-calculations/4410
        #We indicate to the user that the app is searching for results:
        loading(div_html_response)
        curdoc().add_next_tick_callback(update_answer)
        
        
        
        
    #We define the behaviour when the query is modified:
    query_selection.on_change('value', loading_updating_answer)
    #We also want that the query is updated when the task is modified.
    #We define the behaviour when the task is modified:
    #We have modified the function update_query accordingly.
    task_selection.on_change('value', update_query)
    
    
        
        
        
    
    
    #We want to change the responses with the numbers of articles and sentences selected in 
    #the number_articles and number_sentences sliders
    number_articles.on_change('value', loading_updating_answer)
    number_sentences.on_change('value', loading_updating_answer)



    #--------------------------------------------------------------------Plotting the QUERY ----------------------#
    #We plot the query in the graph:
    query_coordinates= PrincipalCA.transform(transform_query(tfidf, query_selection.value))
    [[query_x, query_y]]=query_coordinates

    def update_representation_query():
        #We update the coordinates of the query:
        query_coordinates= PrincipalCA.transform(transform_query(tfidf, query_selection.value))
        [[new_query_x, new_query_y]]=query_coordinates
        new_data_query={'query_x': [new_query_x],'query_y': [new_query_y], 'query': [query_selection.value]}
        source_rep_query.data=new_data_query
    
    #-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------#  
    #Legend behaviour:
    #Doc : https://docs.bokeh.org/en/latest/docs/user_guide/interaction/legends.html
    p.legend.location = "top_right"
    p.legend.click_policy="mute"
    
    
    #Hovers (one for the article points, the over for the query)
    #Tooltips for the hover definition on the representation of the articles:
    tooltips_articles = [("Title", "@title"),('Authors', "@authors"),("url", "@link"),("id", "@index")]

    #Defining the two hovers, with the corresponding names and tooltips:

    p.add_tools(hover_article)
    p.add_tools(hover_query)
    
    
    #We define the link of each glyph as the link column in the DataFrame
    url = "@link"
    taptool = p.select(type=TapTool)
    #We the user taps on a glyph (a circle associated with an article), the url is open
    taptool.callback = OpenURL(url=url)
    
    
    
    #We define the way to plot the different parts of the app:
    #We have the left part with the question-answering

    layout_left=Column(task_selection,query_selection,number_articles, number_sentences,div_html_response)

    year_layout=Row(Column(checkbox_year,slider_year),validate_button_year)
    layout_right=Column(year_layout, p)
    #We define the entire layout:
    entire_layout1=Row(layout_left,layout_right)    
    
    #---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------#

    #-------------------------------FREE SEARCH---------------------------------------------------------------#

            plot_2.visible=True
            free_visualization_button.label='Hide the visualization of your query'

            #We show again the response to the query:
